The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Buddha calls for calm; bar on rallies
                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                      Buddha calls for calm; bar on rallies
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                              
	Calcutta, Sept. 29: Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee today asked the people of Bengal to stay calm over the Ayodhya verdict, underpinning his appeal on the states political maturity and its history of remaining peaceful in tense times.        
	Our state has always shown a lot of political maturity. Even when undesirable incidents have happened in the rest of the country, our state has remained peaceful. I ask all well-meaning people to come forward and ensure the same peace and discipline is maintained tomorrow, the chief minister said after reviewing security with top officials.        
	Bhattacharjee said the assessment on the eve of the ruling indicated the state was peaceful and normal.         
	I have taken stock of the situation in all the districts. Its peaceful and normal everywhere and I appeal to all citizens of the state to ensure it remains that way tomorrow after the verdict on the Ayodhya issue.        
	Despite the authorities understanding that there would be no trouble, Murshidabad, Malda, North and South Dinajpurs, Nadia, Birbhum, Howrah, Hooghly and Asansol have been labelled highly sensitive. In Calcutta, 18 police station areas have been marked that way.        
	Chief secretary Ardhendu Sen, home secretary Samar Ghosh, director-general of police Naparajit Mukherjee, inspector-general (law and order) Surajit Kar Purakayasthya and Calcutta police commissioner Gautam Mohan Chakrabarti attended the meeting.         
	Jawed Shamim, joint police commissioner (headquarters), said tonight that no meetings, rallies and processions would be allowed in Calcutta on the Ayodhya issue tomorrow. If anybody tries to bring out any procession or hold any meetings on this issue, he will be immediately arrested, the officer said.         
	The police are in touch with important and influential people of different religions in all localities, home secretary Ghosh said.        
	Leaves have been cancelled for all officers for the next three days.                                                                                                                                                          
